<HEADLINE>
<P>

<s docid="LA081990-0061" num="6"> ASTRONOMERS SAY ASTEROID CAME CLOSE TO EARTH</s>
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>

<s docid="LA081990-0061" num="7"> By Reuters</s>
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>

<s docid="LA081990-0061" num="8"> SYDNEY, Australia</s>
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>

<s docid="LA081990-0061" num="9"> Australian astronomers said Friday they have discovered an asteroid several hundred yards long that crossed the Earth's orbital path in June.</s>
</P>
<P>

<s docid="LA081990-0061" num="10"> The asteroid, temporarily named 1990MU, came within 1.2 million miles of the Earth's surface and intersected the planet's path around the sun.</s>
</P>
<P>

<s docid="LA081990-0061" num="11"> It was found by astronomers Robert McNaught and Duncan Olsson-Steel, using telescopes at the Siding Spring Observatory near Coonabarabran, New South Wales.</s>
</P>
<P>

<s docid="LA081990-0061" num="12"> They estimate 1990MU to be hundreds of yards long and say it should cross the Earth's path again in two years.</s>
</P>
<P>

<s docid="LA081990-0061" num="13"> About 70 asteroids crossing the Earth's path have been found, but scientists estimate that at least 1,000 exist.</s>

<s docid="LA081990-0061" num="14"> Most asteroids in the solar system are grouped between the orbits of Mars and Jupiter.</s>
</P>
</TEXT>
